lo, theories of epidemics, earthquakes, political crises, and films such as Blow-Up and Blade Runner. With its scope and precision, The Culture of Disaster will appeal to a wide public interested in modern culture, philosophy, and intellectual history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aDisasters in literature. 0aDisasters. 0aWorld politics. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  afrench literary criticism, disaster relief, the enlightenment, obscure power, astrology, angry gods, philosophers, philosophy, natural disasters, violent universe, political concept, post-enlightenment culture, catastrophes, human causes, collective crisis, personal tragedy, plague of 1720, cholera pandemic, shipwrecks, dystopia, identity, memory, technology, control, government, religion, epidemics, earthquakes, crises, intellectual history, modern world.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226358239423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226358239/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles